      <div xml:id="NA336-kiḷavi">
        <p type="edition">iḵtu āṟupārttuṟṟuc colliyatu</p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">This is what was said after experiecing looking at the path.</p>
        </div>
      <div xml:id="NA336">
        <lg type="edition">
<l>            piṇarccuvaṟ paṉṟi tōṉmulaip piṇavoṭu</l>
<l>            kaṇaikkā lēṉal kaimmikak kavartaliṟ</l>
<l>            kallata rarumpuḻai yalkik kāṉavaṉ</l>
<l>            villiṟ ṟanta veṇkōṭ ṭēṟṟaip</l>
<l>            puṉaiyiruṅ katuppiṉ maṉaiyōḷ keṇṭik</l>
<l>            kuṭimuṟai pakukku neṭumalai nāṭa</l>
<l>            vuravucciṉa vēḻa muṟupuli pārkku</l>
<l>            miravi ṉañcā yañcuva laravi</l>
<l>            ṉīraḷaip puṟṟaṅ kāreṉa muṟṟi</l>
<l>            yiraitē reṇkiṉa makaḻum</l>
<l>            varaicēr ciṟuneṟi vārā tīmē.</l>
            </lg>
        <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>O man from the land of long mountains, where the woman of the house</l>
<l rend="indent">with decorated dark hair cuts [and] distributes, according to the home,</l>
<l rend="indent2">the white-tusked male of the rough-naped pig</l>
<l rend="indent3">given by the bow of the forest man,</l>
<l rend="indent4">as it stayed<note place="foot">Presumably <term xml:lang="ta">ēṟṟai</term> is the subject of <term xml:lang="ta">alki</term>, and not <term xml:lang="ta">kāṉavaṉ</term>, so it is the pair of pigs that stay together in the millet field, and the hunter kills only the male.</note> on the difficult forest path of stone [and] sand,</l>
<l rend="indent4">for seizing in excess of the round-stemmed millet</l>
<l rend="indent4">with its skinny-breasted female,</l>
<l>– you don’t fear the night,</l>
<l rend="indent2">when the elephant bull of strong anger looks out for a tiger to attack,</l>
<l rend="indent4">I fear [it].</l>
<l>Don’t come along the small path joining the mountain,</l>
<l rend="indent">where a group of bears searching for prey digs out, the rainy season</l>
<l rend="indent">itself being well on(?)<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">kār eṉa muṟṟi</term>: what is here the function of <term xml:lang="ta">eṉa</term>? And what a strange use of an absolutive (easier would be <term xml:lang="ta">kār muṟṟi eṉa</term>).</note>, the anthill with wet holes for the snake.</l>
        </lg>
      </div>
